                    )</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1948v06</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d798</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">798</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1948-05-12T14:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1948-05-12T14:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-05-12T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-05-12T14:00:00-05:00" n="798" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d798">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">895.00/5–1148: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Political Adviser in Korea</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jacobs</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-05-12T15:00:00-04:00">May 12, 1948—3 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>144. Reur 342, May 11,<note n="1" xml:id="d798fn1">Not printed.</note> Secy made
                    following statement press conference noon May 12: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The Korean people are to be congratulated on the success of Korea’s
                            first democratic election on Monday, held under the observation of the
                            United Nations Temporary Commission on Korea. The fact that some 90
                            percent of the registered voters cast their ballots, despite the lawless
                            efforts of a Communist-dominated minority to prevent or sabotage the
                            election, is a clear revelation that the Korean people are determined to
                            form their own government by democratic means”.<note n="2" xml:id="d798fn2">Dr. Syngman Rhee sent a telegram of thanks through
                                B. C. Limb, Chairman of the Korean Commission, Washington, on May
                                17.</note>
                        </p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
